## Handoff Protocol

Structured handoff format for agent-to-agent transitions. Explicit handoffs reduce context loss.

*Agents: Vadavik, Lojma, Laznik, Cmok, Bagnik, Zlydni, Mokash, Veles.*

### Autonomous Flow

Agents hand off to each other without user intervention where possible. Flow stops only when user input is required.

| Transition | Auto? | User stop? |
|------------|-------|------------|
| Vadavik → Lojma | yes | — |
| Lojma → Mokash + Cmok mockup | yes | — |
| Cmok mockup → User UAT | — | **Yes** — user must approve mockups |
| User UAT → Laznik | — | **Yes** — user confirms to proceed |
| Laznik → Bagnik | yes | — |
| Bagnik (test gate pass) → Cmok build | yes | — |
| Cmok build → Bagnik + Mokash | yes | — |
| Bagnik (code QA pass) → Zlydni | yes | — |
| Bagnik (test gate fail) → Laznik | yes | — |
| Bagnik (code QA fail) → Cmok | yes | — |
| Zlydni → End | — | Optional — user may push |

**Parallel docs (Mokash):** In Claude Code, Mokash is often launched with `background: true` so it runs alongside Lojma or Cmok. In Cursor / Copilot, still pass the same handoff context to Mokash in parallel when the flow calls for docs + design or docs + build — your UI may not expose “background” the same way.

### Principles

- **Interrupt when valuable** — Have a valuable thought → interrupt. Have nothing to add → remain silent.
- **Explicit over implicit** — Never assume context carries; pass it explicitly
- **Structured format** — Use the handoff template below
- **Justify routing** — Explain why the next agent is appropriate
- **Auto-handoff** — When completing, hand off to the next role using the **How to invoke** table above unless a user stop applies

### Handoff Template

When handing off to another agent, include:

```markdown
## Handoff: [From Agent] → [To Agent]

**Context:** [spec | design | mockups | test gate | build | code QA | commit]
**Trigger:** [Task completed | Blocked | User request]
**Feature path:** `.agentic-kit-artefacts/features/YYYY-MM-DD-feature-name/`

### Deliverables
- [Artifact 1]: [path or description]
- [Artifact 2]: [path or description]

### Context
- **Decisions:** [Key decisions made]
- **Constraints:** [Limitations, dependencies]
- **Blockers:** [None | List if any]

### Next Agent
**Invoke:** name the next **role** from the Handoff Map (e.g. `/vadavik`, `/laznik`, `@bagnik`, `@cmok` for build, `@mokash`, `@zlydni`) — those tokens are Claude shortcuts; use the **How to invoke** table for Cursor and Copilot.
**Why:** [One-line justification for this agent]
**Prompt:** [Suggested prompt for next agent]
```

**Feature path rule:** All feature artifacts live in `.agentic-kit-artefacts/features/YYYY-MM-DD-feature-name/`. Include this path in every handoff so the next agent knows where to read/write. When feature is complete, Zlydni moves the folder to `.agentic-kit-artefacts/archive/`.

### Agent-Specific Handoff Checklists

**Vadavik → Lojma:** Open questions listed? Deferred decisions documented? Feature path included?
**Lojma → Cmok:** States matrix for each screen? UX path? Key decisions?
**Lojma → Mokash:** UX path? Key flows to document?
**Laznik → Bagnik:** Coverage summary? Known gaps? Arch path? Test paths?
**Cmok → Bagnik:** Feature path? What was built? Changed files? New storage/API?
**Cmok → Mokash:** What was built? Feature path? Spec/UX/tech plan paths?
**Bagnik → Zlydni:** Bagnik passed. Feature path. Changed files. Safe to commit.

### Handoff Map

| From | To | Invocation | Auto? |
|------|-----|------------|-------|
| Idea/User | Vadavik | `/vadavik` | — |
| Vadavik | Lojma | `/lojma` | yes |
| Lojma | Mokash (parallel) | `@mokash` | yes |
| Lojma | Cmok | `/cmok` (mockups) | yes |
| Cmok mockup | User UAT | — | **STOP** |
| User UAT | Laznik | `/laznik` | **STOP** |
| Laznik | Bagnik | `@bagnik` (test gate) | yes |
| Bagnik (test gate pass) | Cmok | `@cmok` (build) | yes |
| Cmok | Mokash (parallel) | `@mokash` | yes |
| Cmok | Bagnik | `@bagnik` (code QA) | yes |
| Bagnik (code QA pass) | Zlydni | `@zlydni` | yes |
| Bagnik (test gate fail) | Laznik | `/laznik` | yes |
| Bagnik (code QA fail) | Cmok | `@cmok` | yes |
| Zlydni | End | — | Optional push |

*The **Invocation** column is Claude-style shorthand (`/` skills, `@` agents). Same roles elsewhere: **Cursor** — `/` skill picker and **`/subagent-name`** for kit agents (**`/cmok-build`** for implementation). **Copilot** — agents menu (**cmok** agent for build).*

**Bagnik context inference:** Bagnik determines its role from who invoked it. From Laznik = test gate (fail → Laznik, pass → Cmok build). From Cmok = code QA (fail → Cmok, pass → Zlydni). Fix loops repeat until Bagnik passes — no iteration limit.

### Quality Gates

- **Bagnik test gate** — Block if tests fail. Do not proceed to build.
- **Bagnik code QA** — Block if QA fails. Do not proceed to Zlydni.
- **Bagnik security & PII** — Block if security issues or personal data leaks found.
- **Nothing ships without passing Bagnik.** Bagnik does not negotiate.

### Handoff Log

Each feature folder contains a `handoff-log.md` created by **`.claude/skills/vadavik/new-feature.sh <feature-slug>`** (run from project root; `.claude/skills/` is populated by `init.sh` whenever the kit sets up Claude paths — modes `claude`, `cursor`, `github`, or `all`). Every agent appends one entry before handing off:

```markdown
## HH:MM [From] → [To] [context]
Key decisions: ...
Artifacts: ...
```

This gives any agent a full chain of custody when context is lost, especially across Bagnik-Cmok fix loop iterations. `agentic-kit/tools/feature-status.sh` checks whether the log exists.

### Best Practices

1. **Include file paths** — Receiving agent needs to know what to read
2. **Include feature path** — Always pass `.agentic-kit-artefacts/features/YYYY-MM-DD-feature-name/` in handoffs
3. **Summarize decisions** — Don't make the next agent re-derive
4. **Flag blockers early** — Hand back to the appropriate agent
5. **Parallel handoffs** — Mokash can run alongside Lojma or Cmok; pass same context to both
6. **Close feature after commit** — After Zlydni commit, move feature folder to `.agentic-kit-artefacts/archive/`
7. **Version bumping** — Cmok: bump patch before each build. Zlydni: bump minor before commit. Update all version files listed in Project-Specific Configuration.
8. **Mokash handoff template:** Feature path, Spec path, UX path, Tech plan path, What was built, Document: [scope]

## Memory layers

The kit uses a five-layer memory tree (see `agentic-kit/templates/memory/SCHEMA.md`). All agents read **`.agentic-kit-artefacts/MEMORY.md`** (L4) before starting and write to today's L2 file when their checklist triggers fire.

| Layer | Path | Read | Write |
|-------|------|------|-------|
| L0 enforcement | `agents/*.md`, `skills/*/SKILL.md`, `autoresearch/program.md` | yes | only via `apply-patches.sh` or Veles |
| L1 hot state | `.agentic-kit-artefacts/SESSION-STATE.md` | yes | every agent on entry/exit |
| L2 daily | `.agentic-kit-artefacts/memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` | when relevant | append-only per checklist |
| L3 long-term | `.agentic-kit-artefacts/memory/{preferences,system,projects,decisions}.md` | drilldowns from L4 | only via `memory-promote.sh` |
| L4 root summary | `.agentic-kit-artefacts/MEMORY.md` | **first**, always | regenerated by `memory-promote.sh` |
| L5 semantic recall | `agentic-kit/tools/memory-search.sh "<q>"` | when uncertain | n/a |

**Promotion** (`agentic-kit/tools/memory-promote.sh`): observed → logged (L2) → curated (L3 via 2-strike rule) → hardened (L0 patch) → stable. Run after every archive (Zlydni does this automatically).

**Temporal awareness:** entries declaring `supersedes: mem_<id>` cause the older entry to be tagged `[superseded by …]` instead of being deleted (Навь principle — past is preserved, just deprioritised in retrieval).
